This is a function which downloads the file from html and creates a pandas dataframe¶
In [172]:
def url_to_dataframe(str):
    # Download from the url
    current_download = pd.read_html(str)
    
    # Give an initital state which we can append to
    df = current_download[0]
    
    # Append each 
    for i in range(1,len(current_download)):
        df = df.append(current_download[i])
    
    return df
Manipulates a dataframe into a timeseries when month is in int format¶
In [173]:
def dataframe_to_timeseries(df): 
    # Convert the year, month and day columns into one single timedate column
    # to be used as the key
    datelist = []

    for i in range(0,len(df)):
        datelist.append(datetime(df.iloc[i]['Year'],df.iloc[i]['Month'],df.iloc[i]['Day']))
    
    # Insert the Date values into dataframe
    df.insert(value=datelist,column='Date',loc=0)
    
    # Set the key of the dataframe
    df = df.set_index('Date')
    
    return df

Manipulates a dataframe into a timeseries when month is in string format¶
In [175]:
def dataframe_to_timeseries_string(df): 
    # Convert the year, month and day columns into one single timedate column
    # to be used as the key
    datelist = []

    for i in range(0,len(df)):
        datelist.append(datetime(int(df.iloc[i]['Year']),int(months[df.iloc[i]['Month']]),int(df.iloc[i]['Day'])))
    # Insert the Date values into dataframe
    df.insert(value=datelist,column='Date',loc=0)
    
    # Set the key of the dataframe
    df = df.set_index('Date')
    
    return df
This is a function used to remove the row of "-" at the end of each month in some of these datasets¶
In [176]:
def remove_end_month(df):
    df = df[df.Day != ""]
    
    return df
To create a one line setup for each of these types of datasets, we will create two functions, each taking in an input and outputting a completed timeseries which we can then work on. One of these will be for when the month is in int format, while the other will be for when the month is in string format¶
In [177]:
def setup_int(str):
    output = url_to_dataframe(str)
    output = dataframe_to_timeseries(output)
    
    return output

def setup_string(str):
    output = url_to_dataframe(str)
    # Removing the line of "-" at the end of each month
    output = remove_end_month(output)
    output = dataframe_to_timeseries_string(output)
    
    return output

We now have our 4 datasets which we can use for analysis. There is a slight problem however in that the Intel, EA and Amazon datasets have not stored the Open, Close, High and Low columns as floats. We will now write a quick function to fix this.

In [179]:
def switch_to_float(df):
    df["Open"] = df["Open"].astype(float)
    df["Close"] = df["Close"].astype(float)
    df["High"] = df["High"].astype(float)
    df["Low"] = df["Low"].astype(float)
    
    return df

We need to get values to fill the NaN rows which appear in these datasets. For this we will have to fill the 4 columns. For this type of data, the best way in whick to fill these will be to fill them from the front. That is, we will take the previous day's data as the best estimate for the data of the actual day. We will do this for all four datasets.

def is_business_day(date):
    return bool(len(pd.bdate_range(date, date)))

These missing days are exactly what should be expected from analyzing stock prices. As the stock market is closed on certain public holidays every year, aswell as every weekend, we will not analyze the stock price on these days.

The list of public holidays for which the stock market is closed is as follows:

  • New Year's Day
  • Martin Luther King, Jr. Day
  • President's Day
  • Good Friday
  • Memorial Day
  • Independence Day
  • Labor Day
  • Thanksgiving Day
  • Christmas Day

We also have other reasons for the stock market to be closed, for example, in 2012, the stock market was closed on the 29th and 30th of October for Hurricane Sandy

Another way in which we could have analyzed the stock data is by creating data for each of these missing days. I feel however that this would be a misinterpretation of the stock price as we are essentially making up data for days in which the market is closed.

We then see a small dip again, before the stock reaches its max point in the first quarter of 2019.

Upon first look at this stock, the stock seems to become somewhat volatile in 2018, which a lot of changes in price over a relative short period of time.

The ideal trend for a graph such as this would be for there to be mostly positive spikes in the graph. This however is not the case for this chart. While there is a steady enough number of positive spikes evident in this chart, there are also a lot of cases where the price drops significantly.

For an example of this, we can look at the low spike in 2016, when the stock lost almost 10% of its worth in a day. This is a very dangerous prospect for potential investors as it shows unreliability.

While this is counteracted by spikes such as the one at the beginning of 2018 where the stock rose by 10% in a day, there is still a lot of volatility in the stock history for a potential investor.

One final visualisation of this intel data combines all 4 of the data columns in our dataset. This is done using a candelstick chart and is a very effective visualisation method.

In [196]:
intel_candlestick = go.Figure(data=[go.Candlestick(x=intel_df.index,
                    open=intel_df['Open'],
                    high=intel_df['High'],
                    low=intel_df['Low'],
                    close=intel_df['Close'])])

intel_candlestick.update_layout(
    title="Intel 2012-2018",
    xaxis_title="Price",
    yaxis_title="Time",
)

intel_candlestick.show()

This candlestick chart provided by pyplot give us a very useful slider which we can use to view the data over a much shorter period of time.

For example, if we look at the month of September 2019, we can see that the closing price is initially higher than the opening for roughly the first two weeks of the month, but the following week we see this reverse.

While over the entire dataset it might be hard to visualise exactly what is happening in this graph, when focusing in on a single year we can see more accurately the trends which materialise in the data when graphing it in forms such as this candlestick graph.

In summary for this intel stock, we can see that it has been steadily rising over the past 8 years, albeit while still being quite a volatile stock. Steep rises in the late period of 2017 are brought back to Earth slightly with drops in late April 2018 and 2019.

It is interesting to note two major drops in the stock price upon releasing the first quarterly review of the company, a pattern which has appeared in both 2018 and 2019

We can see from this graph that the stock price of EA has also increased over time, albeit a lot more sharply than the intel stock. We have a very gradual rise to the max point, which occured on the 18th of July 2018. This was followed by a massive drop in the stock price, falling from over $140 to under $80 in less than 6 months.

The reasons for this are a poor third quarter of 2018, with games such as Battlefield V failing to meet the expectations EA set for it. By pushing back the release date from October to November, which was announced in late July, the game had to compete with a wider variety of AAA titles like Call of Duty: Black Ops 4 and Red Dead Redemption 2.

Despite this however, we still see a video game developer whos stock prices have risen massively over the period, with potential to grow again in the future with more releases.

For the purpose of analyzing this data, we will also draw the stock data on a simple graph. This time however, we will draw multiple moving average lines in order to show the difference that the moving average will make on the data.

In [209]:
msft_close = msft_df['Close']
msft_mavg_7 = msft_close.rolling(window=7).mean()
msft_mavg_50 = msft_close.rolling(window=50).mean()
msft_mavg_200 = msft_close.rolling(window=200).mean()

msft_df['Close'].plot(figsize=(20, 10),color='red')
plt.title("Analysis of Closing Price for Microsoft using a 7,50,200 Day Moving Average")
plt.grid()
plt.plot(msft_mavg_7,color='b')

plt.ylabel("Price $")
plt.xlabel("Time")
plt.legend()
plt.show()

As we can see from the graph, the period for the moving average is very important for the line which is drawn. As the blue line is the smallest period at 25 days, it is the least smooth of all the lines. In the same vein, as the cyan line is using the largest period of time. As such it is a very smoothed out line.

This is a great visualisation of what the moving average actually shows when used in a graph. It is an excellent method of showing the overall trend of a stock over a time period.

In terms of the data shown by this method, we can see that Microsoft has been a very steady riser over the past 8 years. There is only one very significant drop in price over the entire 8 year period. From this graph, I would expect a very positive heavy return spread.

def concat_columns(str):
    ibm = ibm_df[str]
    intel = intel_df[str]
    ea = ea_df[str]
    microsoft = msft_df[str]
    
    result = { 'IBM' : ibm, 'Intel' : intel, 'EA': ea, 'Microsoft' : microsoft}
    result = pd.DataFrame(result)
    
    return result

From previously using the closing price data correlation, we have now found some meaningful data in which to analyze. One of the main points which is quite clear to see from the heatmap shown above, EA is the company here which has the least correlation with any of the other 3.

This could be accounted to many reasons, but is more than likely due to the fact that EA is a company which produces games, which is not what a lot of people use their PC's or even Windows for. This therefore does not come as much of a surprise that EA has the least relationship with the other stocks.

Final Conclusions¶

We have seen through the individual analysis found above how the 4 chosen companies, IBM, Intel, EA and Microsoft have developed over the past 8 years. In the case of Intel, we have a company who has steadily rose over the past eight years, and has just about doubled in size.

We then have Microsoft, who have increased their price by a scale of 5, with only 1 drop a long the way. Similarly up until mid 2018, we had EA doing the same, before a very sharp drop in price brought them back towards 2017, albeit still much ahead of 2012.

In contrast to this, we have IBM, who started off with more share price then the other 3 companies combined. Since then, IBM share price has plummeted, losing almost 30% of their stock price in the space of 8 years.

We have also noted numerous trends between these datasets. Firstly, we noticed a drop in October 2018, whereby all stocks dropped noticeably within the month, especially EA and IBM. This was part of a wider drop across the entire market. We looked at this especially through analysing Microsofts stock price through Quarter 4 of 2018.

We have also explored correlation between these companies prices, noting mainly the moderate correlation between the daily percent change between Intel and Microsoft. This came as no surprise with the share both of these companies have in the PC market. We attempted to create a formula to predict the price of Intel Stock based on the price of Microsoft through linear regression.

What was surprising however was the correlations between both Intel and Microsoft with IBM. Considering IBM had performed so differently to the others in the period, we expected very little correlation, but in fact were met with a weak-moderate correlation.

With only very little correlations with the other 3 companies, EA would have to be considered the odd one out in this analysis. This makes sense, as despite EA produced games requiring Windows and CPUs to run, the majority of modern PC users are not using their systems for Gaming.

Overall, I attempted to analyse these stocks over varying time periods, both individually and together, and I feel like I have found some sort of meaningful results which tell a lot about each one of these stocks and their 8 year histories
